  "articleSummary": "This article warns against the rigid, dogmatic application of the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), arguing that prioritizing extreme code fragmentation over conceptual cohesion ultimately degrades maintainability, velocity, and developer well-being. Using React/Redux and Unix philosophy as contrasting examples, it demonstrates how over-abstracted architectures create navigational chaos, brittle test suites, and excessive cognitive load. Written in a cautionary, slightly satirical tone, the piece employs recurring metaphors of architectural violence, archaeological excavation, and Rube Goldberg machines to frame the problem. The intended audience is software developers, architects, and engineering leads navigating codebase organization, refactoring, and pragmatic design trade-offs.",
